
Part 1
Compute center of earth to reflector or feature vectors.
Write out vectors with time. Maybe need relativistic correction.

EOP not needed as at center of earth.


Part 2
For each reflector and feature file,
For each time
	Compute lighttime offset between center of earth and station.
	Retard time of interpolation of center of earth state vector by this 
	  amount to get lunar range at the same time as c-of-e.
        Subtract properly rotated station vector from state vector to get state
	  vector at the time of interpolation.
	Do same thing with return leg.
	Compute range from sqrt of sum of squares of leg, for both directions.

Detail:
  Compute outgoing range
  Translate from C-of-E to station
  Compute outgoing range
  Difference the ranges.
  increase interp time by diff in range time
  Computer outgoing range.
  Iterate current and previous range until closure??
  Do same with inbound range.
	 
Format requirements: 
 - EOP
 - outgoing, returning statevector (center of earth and reflector/feature
 - nutation values (4)
 - relativistic correction(s)


Notes on relativistic correction:
This goes as A+B+AB/(A+B-AB). Consider full moon, new moon, and quadrature.
Say the sun-earth distance (A) = 500 sec and AB = 1.25 sec 
Full: B= 500+1.25, and the quotient becomes: 1.0025
New:  B= 500-1.25, and the quotient becomes: 1.002506
Quad: B= 500, and the quotient becomes: 1.002503
So the variation is 5e-6, far below needs for predictions, given an overall
relativistic effect of 25nsec, one way.

Earth-moon distance vary from 1.15 to 1.35 sec, giving values of
Full: 1.0023, 1.0027
New:  1.002305,...
Earth's orbit ellipticity (re-rm)/rm = 0.0034.
Hmmm, One day's test shows that the outbound correction goes from 23.362-
24.230 nsec. Bakleg correction is similar, giving an overall change of 
1.7 nsec.


